<hymn>Come, Thou Fount of Every Blessing (#1001)</hymn> was most popular during the first week. Of the wards that sang new hymns, two thirds of them sang it on June 2nd. My guess is we will never see a hymn hit that kind of popularity again, with the exception of new holiday hymns. Since then, the popularity of <hymn>Come, Thou Fount of Every Blessing (#1001)</hymn> has gone down, and most of the other hymns went up a little bit. 

The other major trend is that <hymn>As Bread is Broken (#1007)</hymn> was very popular on June 16th, Father's day. A common trend was to sing Father's Day songs for opening and closing hymns and that hymn as the sacrament hymn. 

## When during meetings are these hymns sung?

We can see when these hymns tend to be sung and get an overall look at the popularity of the first batch of hymns. If a new hymn is sung, it's likely to be done so as a closing hymn, with the exception of new sacrament hymns. <hymn>Come, Thou Fount of Every Blessing (#1001)</hymn> is often an opening hymn still, but something like <hymn>It Is Well with My Soul (1003)</hymn> is much more likely to be a closing hymn. 


